Date:1/11/2008 10:18:38 AM
From:Spekulatius
AXP - I do not think that the growing debt is the problem - this is part of AXP
growing business. the transactions business requires float and the lending
business is debt. More business means a larger balance sheet. However what i
take offense in is that AXP has whittled down the reserves during the good
times (in terms of % of receivables) and thus shown higher earnings growth than
they would have otherwise. Also their tangible equity looks somewhat low, a
result of stock buybacks.

Now comes the double whammy - the credit losses are going to increase and the
reserves for same need to be boosted. So for roughly 50B$ in outstanding loan
an increase of 1% in credit losses will translate into 500M$ reserve increase
and 500M$ in additional credit losses or a 1B$ earnings impact. 1% increase in
losses is a very possible number, so i can almost guarantee that this 400M$
writeoff will not be the last.

That being said, AXP is a great franchise but i think we are seeing a 3 as a
first number for the stock price first.
